Note: Parser for Runa v0.0.7.5
Note: Line-by-line transliteration from v0.0.7.3 parser.c

Note: Stage1 bootstrap compiler: opt out of name-mangling. Stage1 sources use
Note: bare cross-file function calls (e.g. main.runa calls parser_create
Note: without an Import statement) and rely on the system linker to resolve
Note: them by plain name across .o files. See codegen.runa task #86 commentary.
Let __runa_no_mangle__ be 1

Note: Offsets for program structure (MUST match codegen.runa expectations!)
Note: This layout matches v0.0.7.3 C struct Program
Let PROGRAM_FUNCTIONS be 0      Note: Function **functions
Let PROGRAM_FUNCTION_COUNT be 8 Note: int function_count
Let PROGRAM_FUNCTION_CAPACITY be 12 Note: int function_capacity
Let PROGRAM_TYPES be 16         Note: TypeDefinition **types
Let PROGRAM_TYPE_COUNT be 24    Note: int type_count
Let PROGRAM_TYPE_CAPACITY be 28 Note: int type_capacity
Let PROGRAM_IMPORTS be 32       Note: Import **imports
Let PROGRAM_IMPORT_COUNT be 40  Note: int import_count
Let PROGRAM_IMPORT_CAPACITY be 44 Note: int import_capacity
Let PROGRAM_GLOBAL_VARS be 48   Note: GlobalVariable **globals
Let PROGRAM_GLOBAL_COUNT be 56  Note: int global_count
Let PROGRAM_GLOBAL_CAPACITY be 60 Note: int global_capacity

Note: Helper function to check if a token can be used as an identifier
Note: Some keywords are context-sensitive and can be variable names
Process called "token_can_be_identifier" takes token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Always accept TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
    If token_type is equal to 53:
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 148:  Note: TOKEN_AT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 149:  Note: TOKEN_INDEX
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 150:  Note: TOKEN_KEY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 151:  Note: TOKEN_LENGTH
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 152:  Note: TOKEN_IN
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 153:  Note: TOKEN_WHERE
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 154:  Note: TOKEN_AN
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 156:  Note: TOKEN_CONTAINING
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 144:  Note: TOKEN_FROM
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 145:  Note: TOKEN_EACH
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 159:  Note: TOKEN_LIST
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 160:  Note: TOKEN_DICTIONARY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 155:  Note: TOKEN_A
        Return 1

    Note: Common variable names that are context-sensitive
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 132:  Note: TOKEN_COUNT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 133:  Note: TOKEN_NEGATIVE — context-sensitive: still acts as the unary-negation prefix operator in expression-primary position (parser dispatch on TOKEN_NEGATIVE handles `negative <INT>` literally), but legal as a Let-target / parameter / field identifier name. Resolves Bug #371: `Let negative be 0` previously rejected because TOKEN_NEGATIVE was absent from the identifier-eligibility set. Not added to token_can_continue_identifier — must NOT be swallowed as a multi-word continuation, otherwise expression-parsed text like `Let found_index be negative 1` would merge the operator into the binding name.
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 124:  Note: TOKEN_POINTER
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 129:  Note: TOKEN_ERROR
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 126:  Note: TOKEN_ARRAY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 177:  Note: TOKEN_LEFT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 178:  Note: TOKEN_RIGHT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 175:  Note: TOKEN_BITWISE
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 176:  Note: TOKEN_SHIFTED
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 179:  Note: TOKEN_CONTAINS
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 174:  Note: TOKEN_NOTHING
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 172:  Note: TOKEN_ALERT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 180:  Note: TOKEN_LOOP
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 181:  Note: TOKEN_FOREVER
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 182:  Note: TOKEN_JOINED
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 39:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_AND
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 40:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_OR
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 41:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_XOR
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 42:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_LEFT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 43:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_RIGHT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 16:  Note: TOKEN_PLUS
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 17:  Note: TOKEN_MINUS
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 8:  Note: TOKEN_END
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 15:  Note: TOKEN_TO
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 21:  Note: TOKEN_IS
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 29:  Note: TOKEN_NOT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 30:  Note: TOKEN_AND
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 31:  Note: TOKEN_OR
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 50:  Note: TOKEN_TYPE
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 14:  Note: TOKEN_SET
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 49:  Note: TOKEN_DISPLAY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 162:  Note: TOKEN_LAMBDA (lexer assigns 162; comment was off-by-one)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 164:  Note: TOKEN_CONSTANT (used as variant/field name)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 183:  Note: TOKEN_CALL (used as variant/field/identifier name in non-statement context)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 4:  Note: TOKEN_INTEGER_TYPE (acts as module name in "proc X from Integer with args")
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 5:  Note: TOKEN_STRING_TYPE (acts as module name in "proc X from String with args")
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 6:  Note: TOKEN_CHARACTER_TYPE (acts as module name in "proc X from Character with args")
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
token_can_continue_identifier — multi-word identifier continuation predicate.

Stage 1 dead-code helper (task #95). The first word of an identifier is gated
by token_can_be_identifier above. SECOND and subsequent words inside the same
identifier are gated by this Process instead. The two predicates are intentionally
different because token_can_be_identifier is intentionally LIBERAL — it accepts
operator tokens like TOKEN_PLUS/TOKEN_MINUS/TOKEN_IS/TOKEN_AND/TOKEN_OR/etc. so
that those keywords may appear as legacy single-token variable names; if a
multi-word collector used token_can_be_identifier, it would happily swallow the
"plus" in "x plus y" as a continuation word, ruining every expression.

This predicate is conservative and natural-language-driven. It accepts:
- TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (53) — ordinary identifier words
- TOKEN_AS (34) — freed by the trailing "of type T" migration (task #94/#96);
  motivating example "Let my grades as a highschooler be 12".
- TOKEN_A (155), TOKEN_AN (154) — natural-language articles
- The common context-sensitive variable-name tokens already legal as
  first-word identifiers: TOKEN_COUNT (132), TOKEN_POINTER (124),
  TOKEN_ERROR (129), TOKEN_ARRAY (126), TOKEN_NOTHING (174), TOKEN_ALERT (172),
  TOKEN_LOOP (180), TOKEN_FOREVER (181), TOKEN_JOINED (182), TOKEN_LEFT (177),
  TOKEN_RIGHT (178), TOKEN_BITWISE (175), TOKEN_SHIFTED (176),
  TOKEN_CONTAINS (179)
- Common natural-language suffixes: TOKEN_KEY (150), TOKEN_LENGTH (151),
  TOKEN_INDEX (149) — supports "user key", "string length", "loop index"
- Collection-name nouns: TOKEN_LIST (159), TOKEN_DICTIONARY (160) — supports
  "my list", "the dictionary"
- TOKEN_LAMBDA (162), TOKEN_CONSTANT (164), TOKEN_CALL (183) — already in the
  first-word set as variable-name-eligible keywords
- TOKEN_WHERE (153) — supports "data where filter applies"

Explicitly REJECTED (these would either be operators or clause separators):
- Operators that would otherwise be swallowed inside expressions:
  TOKEN_PLUS (16), TOKEN_MINUS (17), TOKEN_AND (30), TOKEN_OR (31),
  TOKEN_NOT (29), TOKEN_BIT_AND (39), TOKEN_BIT_OR (40), TOKEN_BIT_XOR (41),
  TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_LEFT (42), TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_RIGHT (43)
- Structural keywords that introduce a new construct or end one:
  TOKEN_BE (13), TOKEN_IS (21), TOKEN_TO (15), TOKEN_END (8),
  TOKEN_SET (14), TOKEN_DISPLAY (49), TOKEN_TYPE (50)
- Type-name tokens: TOKEN_INTEGER_TYPE (4), TOKEN_STRING_TYPE (5),
  TOKEN_CHARACTER_TYPE (6) — accepting these would let a multi-word identifier
  greedily eat a type annotation in pre-task#94 code paths.
- Clause keywords that begin a new sub-construct:
  TOKEN_AT (148), TOKEN_IN (152), TOKEN_FROM (144), TOKEN_EACH (145),
  TOKEN_CONTAINING (156), TOKEN_OF (125)

This set is the INITIAL Stage-1 set. Stages 2-13 may tune it as integration
testing surfaces real-world collisions; the predicate is the single point of
truth for "what counts as a continuation word".
:End Note
Process called "token_can_continue_identifier" takes token_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Plain identifier — always a continuation word.
    If token_type is equal to 53:
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 34:  Note: TOKEN_AS (freed by task #94/#96)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 155:  Note: TOKEN_A (article)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 154:  Note: TOKEN_AN (article)
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 132:  Note: TOKEN_COUNT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 124:  Note: TOKEN_POINTER
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 129:  Note: TOKEN_ERROR
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 126:  Note: TOKEN_ARRAY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 174:  Note: TOKEN_NOTHING
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 172:  Note: TOKEN_ALERT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 180:  Note: TOKEN_LOOP
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 181:  Note: TOKEN_FOREVER
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 177:  Note: TOKEN_LEFT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 178:  Note: TOKEN_RIGHT
        Return 1
    Note:
    TOKEN_BITWISE (175), TOKEN_SHIFTED (176), TOKEN_CONTAINS (179), and
    TOKEN_JOINED (182) are EXCLUDED from the continuation set. Each of
    these tokens unambiguously introduces a binary-operator phrase at
    use-position:
      - `X bitwise and/or/xor [by] Y`
      - `X shifted left/right by Y`
      - `X contains Y`           (with optional `key`/`index` discriminator)
      - `X joined with Y`        (string concatenation)
    Including them as continuation words caused the multi-word identifier
    collector to greedily swallow the operator keyword as part of the
    left operand's name (e.g. `value shifted right by amount` was
    collected as identifier `value_shifted_right`, leaving `by` as the
    next token and producing a spurious parser error). The lexer already
    tokenises underscore-joined forms like `bitwise_or` as a single
    TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (since `_` is part of the word-character class in
    lexer_read_word), so the D8 space-underscore equivalence is preserved
    for actual identifier names — only the bare operator triggers are
    excluded here. TOKEN_LEFT (177) and TOKEN_RIGHT (178) remain in the
    continuation set: they only carry operator semantics AFTER
    TOKEN_SHIFTED, never as the lone start of an operator phrase in
    expression context, so they cannot independently misbind. (Bug
    diagnosed via canary_emit_hex_word on memory/layout.runa:1284; see
    DEV-LOGS/104-layout-runa-parser-fix.md.)
    :End Note
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 150:  Note: TOKEN_KEY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 151:  Note: TOKEN_LENGTH
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 149:  Note: TOKEN_INDEX
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 159:  Note: TOKEN_LIST
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 160:  Note: TOKEN_DICTIONARY
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 162:  Note: TOKEN_LAMBDA
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 164:  Note: TOKEN_CONSTANT
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 183:  Note: TOKEN_CALL
        Return 1
    Otherwise If token_type is equal to 153:  Note: TOKEN_WHERE
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
parser_collect_multiword_identifier — multi-word identifier collector.

Stage 1 helper (task #95), upgraded under Stage 3 v2 with the CTO-ratified
SAME-LINE CONTINUATION CONSTRAINT. Reads the current identifier token as
the first word, then greedily collects continuation words from successive
cached tokens. Continuation acceptance requires BOTH:
  (a) token_can_continue_identifier returns 1 for the candidate type, AND
  (b) the candidate token's source line equals the FIRST word's source line.
Words are joined with a single underscore between them — per CEO ruling D8,
spaces and underscores are equivalent in identifier names, and the v0.0.8.5
codebase canonically uses underscore form, so producing "my_count" for
source "my count" means downstream codegen/symbol-table lookups continue
to match their existing storage form without any further canonicalization
at the lookup site.

Same-line constraint rationale (2026-05-23 CTO ruling): the Runa lexer
skips ALL whitespace including newlines and emits NO statement-terminator
tokens. At variable-USE positions in `parser_parse_primary`, the token
following a single-word identifier may be the first token of the NEXT
statement (commonly TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for function-call statements). Without
the same-line constraint, the collector would greedily consume that
next-statement IDENT as a continuation word, producing nonsense joined
names like `token_type_parser_eat`. The same-line constraint stops the
collector at the end of any single-line statement: cross-line consumption
becomes impossible. Multi-word identifiers in idiomatic Runa do not span
lines, so the constraint loses no legitimate program. Token line is
populated by the lexer at offset 16 of the token struct.

Contract:
- Caller has already verified the current token is identifier-eligible
  (token_can_be_identifier returned 1).
- The current token is consumed (eaten) along with every subsequent token
  that (i) token_can_continue_identifier accepts AND (ii) lies on the same
  source line as the first word.
- Returns a freshly heap-allocated, NUL-terminated string containing the
  joined name. Caller owns the allocation.

The parser's "lookahead" is the token cached at parser+8. After each
parser_eat, parser_advance lexes the next token and re-caches it there.
The collector therefore does NOT need lexer save/restore: it inspects the
cached token at parser+8 as the candidate next word, and either commits
(parser_eat consumes it and re-caches the following token) or stops. No
token is consumed unless both gates accept it, so the lexer state is
never disturbed.
:End Note
Process called "parser_collect_multiword_identifier" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: First word — captured from the currently cached token, which the
    Note: caller has already verified is identifier-eligible. We also
    Note: capture the first word's source line (token offset 16) so that
    Note: the continuation loop can enforce the same-line constraint.
    Let mw_first_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let mw_first_type be memory_get_integer(mw_first_token, 0)
    Let mw_first_value be memory_get_pointer(mw_first_token, 8)
    Let mw_first_line be memory_get_int32(mw_first_token, 16)
    Let mw_accum be string_duplicate_parser(mw_first_value)
    parser_eat(parser, mw_first_type)

    Note: Continuation loop. Each iteration inspects the freshly cached token
    Note: at parser+8 as the candidate next word. If it passes BOTH the
    Note: continuation predicate AND the same-line guard, we commit (eat it,
    Note: append "_word" to the accumulator, and the next parser_advance
    Note: inside parser_eat re-caches the following token). Otherwise we
    Note: stop without consuming anything.
    Let mw_loop be 1
    While mw_loop is equal to 1:
        Let mw_cand_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let mw_continue be 0
        Let mw_cand_type be 0
        Let mw_cand_value_dup be 0
        If mw_cand_token is not equal to 0:
            Set mw_cand_type to memory_get_integer(mw_cand_token, 0)
            Let mw_cand_line be memory_get_int32(mw_cand_token, 16)
            If mw_cand_line is equal to mw_first_line:
                Let mw_cand_ok be token_can_continue_identifier(mw_cand_type)
                If mw_cand_ok is equal to 1:
                    Note: Duplicate the candidate's word value before we eat
                    Note: the token; parser_eat -> parser_advance -> token_destroy
                    Note: will free the token-owned string, but our duplicate
                    Note: lives on independently.
                    Set mw_cand_value_dup to string_duplicate_parser(memory_get_pointer(mw_cand_token, 8))
                    Set mw_continue to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If mw_continue is equal to 1:
            Note: Commit: eat the candidate, then append "_word" to the
            Note: accumulator. The accumulator's previous allocation is leaked
            Note: here (per the parser's existing convention — string_concat
            Note: returns a fresh allocation, and intermediate name
            Note: allocations during parsing are not freed; the parser lives
            Note: for one compilation).
            parser_eat(parser, mw_cand_type)
            Let mw_sep be memory_allocate(2)
            memory_set_byte(mw_sep, 0, 95)  Note: '_'
            memory_set_byte(mw_sep, 1, 0)
            Let mw_with_sep be string_concat(mw_accum, mw_sep)
            Let mw_joined be string_concat(mw_with_sep, mw_cand_value_dup)
            Set mw_accum to mw_joined
        Otherwise:
            Set mw_loop to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return mw_accum
End Process

Note:
parser_collect_multiword_identifier_binding — multi-word identifier
collector for BINDING positions.

Task #95 Stages 5-9 architectural addendum. Identical to
parser_collect_multiword_identifier except TOKEN_AS (34) terminates the
collection instead of continuing it. This distinction reflects a
fundamental grammar fact: at BINDING positions (Let-name, For-each
iterator, For-from range variable, Process parameter, Type field name,
Constant name, Lambda parameter), the keyword `as` introduces a type
clause that delimits the identifier — `Let x as Type be V`,
`For each x as Type in C`, `takes x as Type returns R`,
`field as Type`, `Constant N as Type is V`, `lambda (x as Type) -> E`.
At USE positions (expression-level variable references), `as` may
legitimately appear inside a multi-word identifier — the CEO motivating
example "my grades as a highschooler" is a USE-position reference.

Same-line constraint, continuation-set semantics, and underscore-joiner
canonicalization are identical to the base collector. The only
difference is the AS short-circuit at the start of each loop body: if
the candidate token type is TOKEN_AS, we stop before invoking the
continuation predicate.

Contract: same as parser_collect_multiword_identifier — caller has
verified the current token is identifier-eligible; returns a
freshly-allocated NUL-terminated joined-name string.
:End Note
Process called "parser_collect_multiword_identifier_binding" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mwb_first_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let mwb_first_type be memory_get_integer(mwb_first_token, 0)
    Let mwb_first_value be memory_get_pointer(mwb_first_token, 8)
    Let mwb_first_line be memory_get_int32(mwb_first_token, 16)
    Let mwb_accum be string_duplicate_parser(mwb_first_value)
    parser_eat(parser, mwb_first_type)

    Let mwb_loop be 1
    While mwb_loop is equal to 1:
        Let mwb_cand_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let mwb_continue be 0
        Let mwb_cand_type be 0
        Let mwb_cand_value_dup be 0
        If mwb_cand_token is not equal to 0:
            Set mwb_cand_type to memory_get_integer(mwb_cand_token, 0)
            Note: BINDING-context short-circuit: TOKEN_AS (34) always
            Note: delimits an identifier at a binding position. We stop
            Note: BEFORE running the continuation predicate so that
            Note: `Let x as Type`, `takes x as Type`, etc., parse
            Note: correctly with x as a single-word name (or with the
            Note: collected multi-word name accumulated so far).
            If mwb_cand_type is not equal to 34:
                Let mwb_cand_line be memory_get_int32(mwb_cand_token, 16)
                If mwb_cand_line is equal to mwb_first_line:
                    Let mwb_cand_ok be token_can_continue_identifier(mwb_cand_type)
                    If mwb_cand_ok is equal to 1:
                        Set mwb_cand_value_dup to string_duplicate_parser(memory_get_pointer(mwb_cand_token, 8))
                        Set mwb_continue to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If mwb_continue is equal to 1:
            parser_eat(parser, mwb_cand_type)
            Let mwb_sep be memory_allocate(2)
            memory_set_byte(mwb_sep, 0, 95)
            memory_set_byte(mwb_sep, 1, 0)
            Let mwb_with_sep be string_concat(mwb_accum, mwb_sep)
            Let mwb_joined be string_concat(mwb_with_sep, mwb_cand_value_dup)
            Set mwb_accum to mwb_joined
        Otherwise:
            Set mwb_loop to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return mwb_accum
End Process

Note:
name_canonicalize — identifier separator canonicalization helper.

Stage 1 dead-code helper (task #95). Takes a NUL-terminated string and
returns a freshly heap-allocated NUL-terminated copy in which every run of
SPACE (ASCII 32) and/or UNDERSCORE (ASCII 95) characters has been collapsed
to a SINGLE UNDERSCORE. All other characters — letters, digits, punctuation,
including case — are preserved as-is.

Examples:
  "my count"        -> "my_count"
  "my_count"        -> "my_count"   (idempotent)
  "my  count"       -> "my_count"   (double space collapsed)
  "my count_here"   -> "my_count_here"
  "My Count"        -> "My_Count"   (case preserved)
  "my_Count"        -> "my_Count"   (case preserved; NOT equal to "My_Count")

Per CEO ruling D8, identifier comparison is case-sensitive AFTER
canonicalization. This Process normalizes the separator only; the case of
every other character is left exactly as the caller provided.

The collector above already produces underscore-joined names, so this
Process is mostly idempotent on collector output. Its real purpose is the
LOOKUP path: when codegen or the symbol table needs to look up a variable
by a name that may have come from user source containing spaces, the caller
canonicalizes the lookup key, then compares against the stored
(collector-produced, already-underscored) name.

Returns a fresh heap allocation. Caller owns it.
:End Note
Process called "name_canonicalize" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let nc_len be string_length(name)
    Note: The output is at most as long as the input (runs are collapsed,
    Note: never expanded). Allocate len+1 bytes for the worst case + NUL.
    Let nc_alloc_size be nc_len plus 1
    Let nc_out be memory_allocate(nc_alloc_size)

    Let nc_i be 0
    Let nc_j be 0
    Let nc_prev_was_sep be 0
    While nc_i is less than nc_len:
        Let nc_ch be memory_get_byte(name, nc_i)
        Let nc_is_sep be 0
        If nc_ch is equal to 32:
            Set nc_is_sep to 1
        Otherwise If nc_ch is equal to 95:
            Set nc_is_sep to 1
        End If

        If nc_is_sep is equal to 1:
            If nc_prev_was_sep is equal to 0:
                memory_set_byte(nc_out, nc_j, 95)  Note: '_'
                Set nc_j to nc_j plus 1
            End If
            Set nc_prev_was_sep to 1
        Otherwise:
            memory_set_byte(nc_out, nc_j, nc_ch)
            Set nc_j to nc_j plus 1
            Set nc_prev_was_sep to 0
        End If

        Set nc_i to nc_i plus 1
    End While

    memory_set_byte(nc_out, nc_j, 0)  Note: NUL terminator
    Return nc_out
End Process

Note: Parser parse expression - entry point for expression parsing with PEMDAS precedence
Process called "parser_parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return parser_parse_logical_or(parser)
End Process

Note: Parse logical OR expressions
Process called "parser_parse_logical_or" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_logical_and(parser)

    Let loop_or be 1
    While loop_or is equal to 1:
        Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

        If token_type is equal to 31:  Note: TOKEN_OR
            parser_eat(parser, 31)
            Let right be parser_parse_logical_and(parser)
            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, 31, right)
        Otherwise:
            Set loop_or to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parse logical AND expressions
Process called "parser_parse_logical_and" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_comparison_level(parser)

    Let loop_and be 1
    While loop_and is equal to 1:
        Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

        If token_type is equal to 30:  Note: TOKEN_AND
            parser_eat(parser, 30)
            Let right be parser_parse_comparison_level(parser)
            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, 30, right)
        Otherwise:
            Set loop_and to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parse comparison expressions (==, !=, <, >, etc.)
Process called "parser_parse_comparison_level" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Return parser_parse_comparison(parser)
End Process

Note: Parse additive expressions (+ and -)
Process called "parser_parse_additive" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_multiplicative(parser)

    Let loop_additive be 1
    While loop_additive is equal to 1:
        Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

        If token_type is equal to 16:  Note: TOKEN_PLUS
            Let operator be token_type
            parser_eat(parser, 16)
            Let right be parser_parse_multiplicative(parser)
            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
        Otherwise If token_type is equal to 17:
            Note: TOKEN_MINUS
            parser_eat(parser, 17)
            Set right to parser_parse_multiplicative(parser)
            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, 17, right)
        Otherwise If token_type is equal to 182:
            Note: TOKEN_JOINED - "joined with" → string_concat(left, right)
            parser_eat(parser, 182)
            parser_eat(parser, 114)  Note: Eat 'with' (TOKEN_WITH = 114)
            Set right to parser_parse_multiplicative(parser)
            Note: Desugar to string_concat(left, right) function call
            Let concat_args be allocate(16)
            memory_set_pointer(concat_args, 0, left)
            memory_set_pointer(concat_args, 8, right)
            Set left to expression_create_function_call(string_duplicate_parser("string_concat"), concat_args, 2)
        Otherwise:
            Set loop_additive to 0
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parse multiplicative expressions (*, /, %)
Process called "parser_parse_multiplicative" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)

    Let loop_multiplicative be 1
    While loop_multiplicative is equal to 1:
        Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

        If token_type is equal to 35:  Note: TOKEN_MULTIPLIED
            Let operator be token_type
            parser_eat(parser, 35)
            parser_eat(parser, 38)
            Let right be parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
        Otherwise:
            If token_type is equal to 36:  Note: TOKEN_DIVIDED
                Set operator to token_type
                parser_eat(parser, 36)
                parser_eat(parser, 38)
                Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
            Otherwise:
                If token_type is equal to 37:  Note: TOKEN_MODULO
                    Set operator to token_type
                    parser_eat(parser, 37)
                    parser_eat(parser, 38)
                    Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                    Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                Otherwise:
                    If token_type is equal to 42:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_LEFT
                        Set operator to token_type
                        parser_eat(parser, 42)
                        Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                        Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                    Otherwise:
                        If token_type is equal to 43:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_RIGHT
                            Set operator to token_type
                            parser_eat(parser, 43)
                            Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                        Otherwise:
                            If token_type is equal to 39:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_AND
                                Set operator to token_type
                                parser_eat(parser, 39)
                                Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                                Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                            Otherwise:
                                If token_type is equal to 40:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_OR
                                    Set operator to token_type
                                    parser_eat(parser, 40)
                                    Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                                    Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                                Otherwise:
                                    If token_type is equal to 41:  Note: TOKEN_BIT_XOR
                                        Set operator to token_type
                                        parser_eat(parser, 41)
                                        Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                                        Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                                    Otherwise:
                                        Note: Handle "bitwise and/or/xor [by]" multi-word operators
                                        If token_type is equal to 175:
                                            parser_eat(parser, 175)  Note: Eat 'bitwise'
                                            Let bw_next be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                                            Let bw_next_type be memory_get_integer(bw_next, 0)
                                            Set operator to 39  Note: Default to BIT_AND
                                            If bw_next_type is equal to 30:
                                                Note: TOKEN_AND -> bitwise and
                                                parser_eat(parser, 30)
                                                Set operator to 39
                                            Otherwise If bw_next_type is equal to 31:
                                                Note: TOKEN_OR -> bitwise or
                                                parser_eat(parser, 31)
                                                Set operator to 40
                                            Otherwise:
                                                Note: Check for xor (identifier)
                                                Let bw_next_val be memory_get_pointer(bw_next, 8)
                                                Let is_xor be 0
                                                If bw_next_val is not equal to 0:
                                                    Set is_xor to string_equals(bw_next_val, "xor")
                                                End If
                                                If is_xor is equal to 1:
                                                    parser_eat(parser, bw_next_type)
                                                    Set operator to 41
                                                Otherwise:
                                                    Note: Unknown bitwise operator - default to and
                                                    parser_eat(parser, bw_next_type)
                                                End If
                                            End If
                                            Note: Optional 'by' between operator and operand (canonical
                                            Note: form is "bitwise and/or/xor by N" mirroring "multiplied
                                            Note: by"; older code accepted the operator without 'by').
                                            Let bw_after_op be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                                            Let bw_after_op_type be memory_get_integer(bw_after_op, 0)
                                            If bw_after_op_type is equal to 38:
                                                parser_eat(parser, 38)
                                            End If
                                            Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                                            Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                                        Otherwise:
                                            Note: Handle "shifted left/right by" multi-word operators
                                            If token_type is equal to 176:
                                                parser_eat(parser, 176)  Note: Eat 'shifted'
                                                Let sh_dir be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                                                Let sh_dir_type be memory_get_integer(sh_dir, 0)
                                                If sh_dir_type is equal to 177:
                                                    Note: TOKEN_LEFT -> shifted left by
                                                    parser_eat(parser, 177)
                                                    parser_eat(parser, 38)  Note: Eat 'by'
                                                    Set operator to 42  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_LEFT
                                                End If
                                                If sh_dir_type is equal to 178:
                                                    Note: TOKEN_RIGHT -> shifted right by
                                                    parser_eat(parser, 178)
                                                    parser_eat(parser, 38)  Note: Eat 'by'
                                                    Set operator to 43  Note: TOKEN_BIT_SHIFT_RIGHT
                                                End If
                                                Set right to parser_parse_primary_with_postfix(parser)
                                                Set left to expression_create_binary_op(left, operator, right)
                                            Otherwise:
                                                Set loop_multiplicative to 0
                                            End If
                                        End If
                                    End If
                                End If
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parse primary expressions with postfix operators (function calls, field access, array indexing)
Process called "parser_parse_primary_with_postfix" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_primary(parser)

    Note: Check for "X at Y" collection indexing → list_get(X, Y)
    Let at_check be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
    Let at_check_type be memory_get_int32(at_check, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
    If at_check_type is equal to 148:
        parser_eat(parser, 148)  Note: Eat 'at'
        Note: Check for optional 'index' or 'key' keyword
        Let at_next be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
        Let at_next_type be memory_get_int32(at_next, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
        If at_next_type is equal to 149:
            parser_eat(parser, 149)  Note: Eat 'index'
        End If
        If at_next_type is equal to 150:
            parser_eat(parser, 150)  Note: Eat 'key'
        End If
        Let at_index be parser_parse_primary(parser)
        Let at_args be allocate(16)
        memory_set_pointer(at_args, 0, left)
        memory_set_pointer(at_args, 8, at_index)
        Set left to expression_create_function_call(string_duplicate_parser("list_get"), at_args, 2)
    End If

    Note: Check for function call (if primary was an identifier and followed by '(')
    Let current_token_fc be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let token_type_fc be memory_get_integer(current_token_fc, 0)
    If token_type_fc is equal to 48:  Note: TOKEN_LPAREN (48)
        Note: Convert variable expression to function call
        Let expr_type be memory_get_integer(left, 0)
        If expr_type is equal to EXPR_VARIABLE:
            Note: Get the variable name from the EXPR_VARIABLE
            Let var_name be memory_get_pointer(left, 8)

            Note: Parse function arguments
            parser_eat(parser, 48)

            Note: Allocate space for arguments
            Let arguments be 0
            Let argument_count be 0
            Let argument_capacity be 4
            Let arg_ptr_size be 8
            Let arg_size be argument_capacity multiplied by arg_ptr_size
            Set arguments to memory_allocate(arg_size)

            Note: Parse arguments until we hit ')'
            Let continue_args be 1
            While continue_args is equal to 1:
                Let current_token_arg be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                Let token_type_arg be memory_get_integer(current_token_arg, 0)

                If token_type_arg is equal to 49:  Note: TOKEN_RPAREN (49)
                    Set continue_args to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Parse the argument expression — use full expression so
                    Note: comparison and logical operators work as args (e.g.
                    Note: `assert(x is less than y)`).  Comma still separates args
                    Note: at this level because parser_parse_expression doesn't eat it.
                    Let arg_expr be parser_parse_expression(parser)

                    Note: Grow array if needed
                    If argument_count is greater than or equal to argument_capacity:
                        Set argument_capacity to argument_capacity multiplied by 2
                        Let new_arg_size be argument_capacity multiplied by arg_ptr_size
                        Set arguments to memory_reallocate(arguments, new_arg_size)
                    End If

                    Note: Store argument
                    Let arg_offset be argument_count multiplied by arg_ptr_size
                    Let arg_ptr be arguments plus arg_offset
                    memory_set_pointer(arg_ptr, 0, arg_expr)
                    Set argument_count to argument_count plus 1

                    Note: Check for comma
                    Let current_token_comma be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                    Let token_type_comma be memory_get_integer(current_token_comma, 0)
                    If token_type_comma is equal to 52:  Note: TOKEN_COMMA (52)
                        parser_eat(parser, 52)
                    End If
                End If
            End While

            parser_eat(parser, 49)

            Note: Create function call expression
            Let func_call be expression_create_function_call(var_name, arguments, argument_count)
            deallocate(left)  Note: Free the old EXPR_VARIABLE
            Set left to func_call
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for lambda call with "with" keyword (e.g., "double with 5" or "add with 3 and 5")
    Set current_token_fc to memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Set token_type_fc to memory_get_integer(current_token_fc, 0)
    If token_type_fc is equal to 114:  Note: TOKEN_WITH (114)
        Note: This is a lambda invocation
        parser_eat(parser, 114)  Note: Eat "with"

        Note: Parse arguments (may be multiple with "and" separator).
        Note: Parallel arg_names array tracks named-arg metadata. Each slot is
        Note: NULL for positional args, or a heap string for `NAME as VAL`.
        Set arguments to 0
        Set argument_count to 0
        Let arg_capacity be 4
        Set arg_size to arg_capacity multiplied by 8
        Set arguments to memory_allocate(arg_size)
        Let pf_arg_names be memory_allocate(arg_size)
        Let pf_any_named be 0
        Let pf_init_i be 0
        While pf_init_i is less than arg_capacity:
            memory_set_pointer(pf_arg_names, pf_init_i multiplied by 8, 0)
            Set pf_init_i to pf_init_i plus 1
        End While

        Let pf_name_slot be memory_allocate(8)

        Note: Parse first argument. Detect named-arg pattern via capture helper.
        Set arg_expr to parser_parse_additive(parser)
        Set arg_expr to parser_handle_named_arg_capture(parser, arg_expr, pf_name_slot)
        Let pf_first_name be memory_get_pointer(pf_name_slot, 0)
        Let last_was_named be 0
        If pf_first_name is not equal to 0:
            Set last_was_named to 1
            Set pf_any_named to 1
        End If
        memory_set_pointer(arguments, 0, arg_expr)
        memory_set_pointer(pf_arg_names, 0, pf_first_name)
        Set argument_count to 1

        Note: Parse additional arguments with "and" keyword OR comma separator.
        Note: The `with X, Y, Z` form mirrors function-call argument syntax for
        Note: callers who write `proc f with arg1, arg2, arg3` (canonical) and
        Note: callers who write `proc f with arg1 and arg2 and arg3` (alt form).
        Set continue_args to 1
        While continue_args is equal to 1:
            Let next_arg_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let next_arg_type be memory_get_int32(next_arg_token, 0)

            Let arg_separator_consumed be 0
            If next_arg_type is equal to 30:
                parser_eat(parser, 30)
                Set arg_separator_consumed to 1
            End If
            If next_arg_type is equal to 52:
                Note: Use struct-field-after-comma peek: if comma is followed by
                Note: `<ident-or-string-literal> as ...` it belongs to a struct
                Note: literal one frame up, not to this argument list.
                Note: But when the previous arg was a named arg (e.g.
                Note: `with name as value, ...`), the comma is unambiguously an
                Note: arg separator for the next named arg — skip the peek.
                Note: Also: when we've already parsed ≥1 arg in this call AND the
                Note: lookahead pattern is `IDENT as`, it's a NAMED arg in our
                Note: list, not a sibling struct-field initializer. Outer struct
                Note: ctor would have terminated us with the first comma; if we're
                Note: still parsing after one arg, we own all subsequent commas.
                Let take_separator be 0
                If last_was_named is equal to 1:
                    Set take_separator to 1
                Otherwise If argument_count is greater than or equal to 1:
                    Set take_separator to 1
                Otherwise:
                    Let lc_field_ahead be parser_peek_struct_field_after_comma(parser)
                    If lc_field_ahead is equal to 0:
                        Set take_separator to 1
                    End If
                End If
                If take_separator is equal to 1:
                    parser_eat(parser, 52)
                    Set arg_separator_consumed to 1
                End If
            End If

            If arg_separator_consumed is equal to 1:
                If argument_count is greater than or equal to arg_capacity:
                    Let pf_old_cap be arg_capacity
                    Set arg_capacity to arg_capacity multiplied by 2
                    Set arg_size to arg_capacity multiplied by 8
                    Set arguments to memory_reallocate(arguments, arg_size)
                    Set pf_arg_names to memory_reallocate(pf_arg_names, arg_size)
                    Let pf_zi be pf_old_cap
                    While pf_zi is less than arg_capacity:
                        memory_set_pointer(pf_arg_names, pf_zi multiplied by 8, 0)
                        Set pf_zi to pf_zi plus 1
                    End While
                End If

                Let arg_expr2 be parser_parse_additive(parser)
                Set arg_expr2 to parser_handle_named_arg_capture(parser, arg_expr2, pf_name_slot)
                Let pf_next_name be memory_get_pointer(pf_name_slot, 0)
                Set last_was_named to 0
                If pf_next_name is not equal to 0:
                    Set last_was_named to 1
                    Set pf_any_named to 1
                End If
                Set arg_offset to argument_count multiplied by 8
                memory_set_pointer(arguments plus arg_offset, 0, arg_expr2)
                memory_set_pointer(pf_arg_names plus arg_offset, 0, pf_next_name)
                Set argument_count to argument_count plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set continue_args to 0
            End If
        End While
        deallocate(pf_name_slot)

        If pf_any_named is equal to 0:
            deallocate(pf_arg_names)
            Set pf_arg_names to 0
        End If

        Note: Decide between a regular function call and a lambda invocation.
        Note: When left is an EXPR_VARIABLE the "with" form names a top-level function
        Note: (e.g. "create_lua_function with arg1 and arg2"); the codegen for
        Note: EXPR_LAMBDA_CALL requires a closure structure and segfaults on a plain
        Note: variable.  Lower this case to EXPR_FUNCTION_CALL using the variable's
        Note: name so it routes through the normal function-call codegen path.
        Set left to with_promote_to_call_or_lambda(left, arguments, argument_count)
        If pf_arg_names is not equal to 0:
            expression_attach_arg_names(left, pf_arg_names)
        End If
    End If

    Note: Handle field access and array indexing (highest precedence)
    Let loop_field be 1
    While loop_field is equal to 1:
        Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

        If token_type is equal to 51:  Note: TOKEN_DOT
            parser_eat(parser, 51)

            Let current_token2 be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let token_type2 be memory_get_integer(current_token2, 0)
            Let dot_can_id be token_can_be_identifier(token_type2)
            If dot_can_id is not equal to 1:
                If token_type2 is not equal to 53:
                    print_string("[PARSER WARNING] Unexpected token after '.' at line ")
                    Let dot_line be memory_get_int32(current_token2, 16)
                    print_integer(dot_line)
                    print_newline()
                End If
            End If

            Note:
            Read the field-access RHS via the binding-context multi-word
            collector — task #95 Stage 10. The binding collector reads
            the first word and joins same-line non-AS continuation
            tokens with single underscores (D8 canonicalization).
            Critical Stage 10 invariant: `obj.field plus 5` must parse
            as `(obj.field) plus 5`, NOT `obj.(field plus 5)`. The
            continuation set excludes TOKEN_PLUS (16) and all binary
            operators (per Stage 1 design), so the collector terminates
            at `plus`. Same-line constraint (Stage 3 v2) prevents
            cross-statement consumption of the next statement's first
            identifier. For a single-word field name, the loop exits
            immediately and the returned name is byte-identical to
            what the previous string_duplicate_parser + parser_eat
            path produced.
            :End Note
            Let field_name be parser_collect_multiword_identifier_binding(parser)
            Let next_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let next_type be memory_get_integer(next_token, 0)
            If next_type is equal to 48:  Note: TOKEN_LPAREN - this is module.function()
                Note: Extract module name from left expression
                Let left_type be memory_get_integer(left, 0)
                If left_type is not equal to EXPR_VARIABLE:
                    print_string("[PARSER ERROR] Module name must be a simple identifier")
                    print_newline()
                    exit_with_code(1)
                End If
                Let module_name be memory_get_pointer(left, 8)  Note: Get var_name from EXPR_VARIABLE

                Note: Parse function arguments
                parser_eat(parser, 48)  Note: '('
                Let qual_args be 0
                Let qual_argc be 0
                Let qual_args_cap be 4
                Let qual_arg_ptrsize be 8
                Let qual_args_size be qual_args_cap multiplied by qual_arg_ptrsize
                Set qual_args to memory_allocate(qual_args_size)

                Note: Parse arguments until ')'. Capacity-doubling grow mirrors
                Note: parser_parse_proc_expression's `with` arg loop so dotted-form
                Note: calls (Module.fn(a,b,...)) accept the full Runa-supported arg
                Note: count rather than overflowing the initial 4-slot buffer at the
                Note: 5th argument. Heap corruption from the overflow surfaced
                Note: downstream as `[CODEGEN ERROR] Unsupported expression type` with
                Note: a raw pointer value when stage1 read past the buffer end.
                Let qual_continue be 1
                While qual_continue is equal to 1:
                    Let qual_arg_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                    Let qual_arg_type be memory_get_integer(qual_arg_token, 0)
                    If qual_arg_type is equal to 49:  Note: TOKEN_RPAREN
                        Set qual_continue to 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Note: Grow before write: if the next slot is past capacity,
                        Note: double the capacity and reallocate. Identical pattern to
                        Note: the proc-from-Module loop.
                        If qual_argc is greater than or equal to qual_args_cap:
                            Set qual_args_cap to qual_args_cap multiplied by 2
                            Set qual_args_size to qual_args_cap multiplied by qual_arg_ptrsize
                            Set qual_args to memory_reallocate(qual_args, qual_args_size)
                        End If
                        Note: Use full expression so comparison and logical ops work as
                        Note: args (e.g. `T.assert_true(x is less than y)`).
                        Let qual_arg_expr be parser_parse_expression(parser)
                        Let qual_arg_off be qual_argc multiplied by qual_arg_ptrsize
                        Let qual_arg_ptr be qual_args plus qual_arg_off
                        memory_set_pointer(qual_arg_ptr, 0, qual_arg_expr)
                        Set qual_argc to qual_argc plus 1

                        Note: Check for comma
                        Let qual_comma_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                        Let qual_comma_type be memory_get_integer(qual_comma_tok, 0)
                        If qual_comma_type is equal to 52:  Note: TOKEN_COMMA
                            parser_eat(parser, 52)
                        End If
                    End If
                End While
                parser_eat(parser, 49)  Note: ')'

                Note: Create EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL: module_name, function_name, arguments, arg_count
                Let qualified_call be memory_allocate(48)
                memory_set_integer(qualified_call, 0, EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL)
                memory_set_pointer(qualified_call, 8, module_name)  Note: module_name
                memory_set_pointer(qualified_call, 16, field_name)  Note: function_name
                memory_set_pointer(qualified_call, 24, qual_args)  Note: arguments
                memory_set_int32(qualified_call, 32, qual_argc)  Note: arg_count
                memory_set_pointer(qualified_call, 40, 0)  Note: arg_names = NULL (positional)
                deallocate(left)  Note: Free the EXPR_VARIABLE
                Set left to qualified_call
            Otherwise:
                Note: `Module.IDENTIFIER` (no parentheses) is module-qualified
                Note: constant access. The bootstrap import system flattens
                Note: namespaces - constants and globals from imported modules
                Note: are merged into the main program by name. So when `left`
                Note: is a bare variable whose name matches a known import
                Note: alias, rewrite the access to a plain reference to the
                Note: identifier, matching how `Module.func()` is rewritten to
                Note: a plain function call (see EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL codegen,
                Note: which strips the module prefix at emit time).
                Let mqc_left_type be memory_get_int32(left, 0)
                Let mqc_is_module be 0
                If mqc_left_type is equal to 1:  Note: EXPR_VARIABLE
                    Let mqc_left_name be memory_get_pointer(left, 8)
                    Let mqc_program be memory_get_pointer(parser, 16)  Note: parser->current_program
                    If mqc_program is not equal to 0:
                        Let mqc_imp_count be memory_get_int32(mqc_program, 40)
                        Let mqc_imports be memory_get_pointer(mqc_program, 32)
                        If mqc_imports is not equal to 0:
                            Let mqc_i be 0
                            While mqc_i is less than mqc_imp_count:
                                Let mqc_imp_off be mqc_i multiplied by 8
                                Let mqc_imp_ptr be memory_get_pointer(mqc_imports, mqc_imp_off)
                                If mqc_imp_ptr is not equal to 0:
                                    Let mqc_mod_name be memory_get_pointer(mqc_imp_ptr, 8)
                                    If string_equals(mqc_mod_name, mqc_left_name) is equal to 1:
                                        Set mqc_is_module to 1
                                        Set mqc_i to mqc_imp_count
                                    End If
                                End If
                                Set mqc_i to mqc_i plus 1
                            End While
                        End If
                    End If
                End If

                If mqc_is_module is equal to 1:
                    Note: Translate `Module.IDENTIFIER` to a bare variable reference
                    Note: against the merged global namespace.
                    Set left to expression_create_variable(field_name)
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Regular field access (not a function call, not a module constant)
                    Let field_access be memory_allocate(32)  Note: sizeof(Expression)
                    memory_set_int32(field_access, 0, 6)  Note: EXPR_FIELD_ACCESS
                    memory_set_pointer(field_access, 8, left)  Note: field_access.object
                    memory_set_pointer(field_access, 16, field_name)  Note: field_access.field_name
                    Set left to field_access
                End If
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 148:  Note: TOKEN_AT (canonical: "at index" or "at key")
            Note: Peek ahead to check if "index" or "key" follows
            parser_eat(parser, 148)  Note: at
            Set current_token to memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
            Set token_type to memory_get_int32(current_token, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)

            Note: Both "at index" (list/array indexing) and "at key" (dictionary keying)
            Note: lower to EXPR_ARRAY_INDEX — codegen distinguishes by runtime type.
            Let at_is_index be 0
            If token_type is equal to 149:
                Set at_is_index to 1
            End If
            If token_type is equal to 150:
                Set at_is_index to 1
            End If
            If at_is_index is equal to 1:
                parser_eat(parser, token_type)  Note: index or key

                Let index be parser_parse_additive(parser)

                Let array_index be memory_allocate(32)
                memory_set_integer(array_index, 0, 16)  Note: EXPR_ARRAY_INDEX
                memory_set_pointer(array_index, 8, left)
                memory_set_pointer(array_index, 16, index)
                Set left to array_index
            Otherwise:
                print_string("[PARSER ERROR] Expected 'index' or 'key' after 'at' at line ")
                Let error_line be memory_get_int32(current_token, TOKEN_LINE_OFFSET)
                print_integer(error_line)
                print_newline()
                exit(1)
            End If
        End If

        If token_type is not equal to 51:
            If token_type is not equal to 148:
                Set loop_field to 0
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: After dot-postfix loop, check for `with args` again to handle
    Note: `Module.method with args` (and `obj.field with args` lambda form),
    Note: which the earlier `with` check (before the loop) cannot see because
    Note: the field access hasn't been parsed yet at that point.
    Let pwp_after_field_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let pwp_after_field_type be memory_get_integer(pwp_after_field_tok, 0)
    If pwp_after_field_type is equal to 114:
        parser_eat(parser, 114)  Note: Eat 'with'

        Let pwp_args be 0
        Let pwp_argc be 0
        Let pwp_arg_cap be 4
        Let pwp_arg_size be pwp_arg_cap multiplied by 8
        Set pwp_args to memory_allocate(pwp_arg_size)
        Let pwp_arg_names be memory_allocate(pwp_arg_size)
        Let pwp_any_named be 0
        Let pwp_init_i be 0
        While pwp_init_i is less than pwp_arg_cap:
            memory_set_pointer(pwp_arg_names, pwp_init_i multiplied by 8, 0)
            Set pwp_init_i to pwp_init_i plus 1
        End While

        Let pwp_name_slot be memory_allocate(8)

        Note: Parse first argument, with named-arg detection.
        Let pwp_arg_expr be parser_parse_additive(parser)
        Set pwp_arg_expr to parser_handle_named_arg_capture(parser, pwp_arg_expr, pwp_name_slot)
        Let pwp_first_name be memory_get_pointer(pwp_name_slot, 0)
        Let pwp_last_named be 0
        If pwp_first_name is not equal to 0:
            Set pwp_last_named to 1
            Set pwp_any_named to 1
        End If
        memory_set_pointer(pwp_args, 0, pwp_arg_expr)
        memory_set_pointer(pwp_arg_names, 0, pwp_first_name)
        Set pwp_argc to 1

        Note: Parse additional arguments with `and` or `,` separator
        Let pwp_continue be 1
        While pwp_continue is equal to 1:
            Let pwp_sep_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let pwp_sep_type be memory_get_int32(pwp_sep_tok, 0)
            Let pwp_sep_consumed be 0
            If pwp_sep_type is equal to 30:
                parser_eat(parser, 30)
                Set pwp_sep_consumed to 1
            End If
            If pwp_sep_type is equal to 52:
                Let pwp_take_sep be 0
                If pwp_last_named is equal to 1:
                    Set pwp_take_sep to 1
                Otherwise:
                    Let pwp_field_ahead be parser_peek_struct_field_after_comma(parser)
                    If pwp_field_ahead is equal to 0:
                        Set pwp_take_sep to 1
                    End If
                End If
                If pwp_take_sep is equal to 1:
                    parser_eat(parser, 52)
                    Set pwp_sep_consumed to 1
                End If
            End If
            If pwp_sep_consumed is equal to 1:
                If pwp_argc is greater than or equal to pwp_arg_cap:
                    Let pwp_old_cap be pwp_arg_cap
                    Set pwp_arg_cap to pwp_arg_cap multiplied by 2
                    Set pwp_arg_size to pwp_arg_cap multiplied by 8
                    Set pwp_args to memory_reallocate(pwp_args, pwp_arg_size)
                    Set pwp_arg_names to memory_reallocate(pwp_arg_names, pwp_arg_size)
                    Let pwp_zi be pwp_old_cap
                    While pwp_zi is less than pwp_arg_cap:
                        memory_set_pointer(pwp_arg_names, pwp_zi multiplied by 8, 0)
                        Set pwp_zi to pwp_zi plus 1
                    End While
                End If
                Let pwp_arg_expr2 be parser_parse_additive(parser)
                Set pwp_arg_expr2 to parser_handle_named_arg_capture(parser, pwp_arg_expr2, pwp_name_slot)
                Let pwp_next_name be memory_get_pointer(pwp_name_slot, 0)
                Set pwp_last_named to 0
                If pwp_next_name is not equal to 0:
                    Set pwp_last_named to 1
                    Set pwp_any_named to 1
                End If
                Let pwp_arg_offset be pwp_argc multiplied by 8
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_args plus pwp_arg_offset, 0, pwp_arg_expr2)
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_arg_names plus pwp_arg_offset, 0, pwp_next_name)
                Set pwp_argc to pwp_argc plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Set pwp_continue to 0
            End If
        End While
        deallocate(pwp_name_slot)

        If pwp_any_named is equal to 0:
            deallocate(pwp_arg_names)
            Set pwp_arg_names to 0
        End If

        Note: Lower to EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL when left is EXPR_FIELD_ACCESS on a
        Note: bare module name (Module.method); otherwise lower to plain call.
        Let pwp_left_type be memory_get_int32(left, 0)
        If pwp_left_type is equal to 6:
            Note: EXPR_FIELD_ACCESS - check if object is bare module variable
            Let pwp_obj be memory_get_pointer(left, 8)
            Let pwp_field_name be memory_get_pointer(left, 16)
            Let pwp_obj_type be memory_get_int32(pwp_obj, 0)
            If pwp_obj_type is equal to 1:
                Note: object is EXPR_VARIABLE - module name
                Let pwp_mod_name be memory_get_pointer(pwp_obj, 8)
                Let pwp_qcall be memory_allocate(48)
                memory_set_integer(pwp_qcall, 0, EXPR_QUALIFIED_CALL)
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_qcall, 8, pwp_mod_name)
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_qcall, 16, pwp_field_name)
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_qcall, 24, pwp_args)
                memory_set_int32(pwp_qcall, 32, pwp_argc)
                memory_set_pointer(pwp_qcall, 40, pwp_arg_names)
                Set left to pwp_qcall
            Otherwise:
                Set left to with_promote_to_call_or_lambda(left, pwp_args, pwp_argc)
                If pwp_arg_names is not equal to 0:
                    expression_attach_arg_names(left, pwp_arg_names)
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set left to with_promote_to_call_or_lambda(left, pwp_args, pwp_argc)
            If pwp_arg_names is not equal to 0:
                expression_attach_arg_names(left, pwp_arg_names)
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parser parse comparison - handles comparison operators
Process called "parser_parse_comparison" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Let left be parser_parse_additive(parser)

    Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)

    If token_type is equal to 21:  Note: TOKEN_IS
        parser_eat(parser, 21)

        Let current_token2 be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Let token_type2 be memory_get_integer(current_token2, 0)

        Note: Check for "not" negation
        Let is_negated be 0
        If token_type2 is equal to 29:  Note: TOKEN_NOT
            parser_eat(parser, 29)
            Set is_negated to 1
            Set current_token2 to memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Set token_type2 to memory_get_integer(current_token2, 0)
        End If

        Let comparison_op be 0

        Note: Handle EQUAL / NOT EQUAL
        If token_type2 is equal to 22:  Note: TOKEN_EQUAL
            parser_eat(parser, 22)
            parser_eat(parser, 15)  Note: TOKEN_TO
            If is_negated is equal to 1:
                Set comparison_op to 23  Note: TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL
            Otherwise:
                Set comparison_op to 22  Note: TOKEN_EQUAL
            End If
        End If

        Note: Handle LESS THAN (and LESS EQUAL)
        If token_type2 is equal to 24:
            parser_eat(parser, 24)
            Let current_token3 be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let token_type3 be memory_get_integer(current_token3, 0)
            If token_type3 is equal to 28:  Note: TOKEN_THAN
                parser_eat(parser, 28)
                Let current_token4 be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                Let token_type4 be memory_get_integer(current_token4, 0)
                If token_type4 is equal to 31:  Note: TOKEN_OR (for "or equal to")
                    parser_eat(parser, 31)
                    parser_eat(parser, 22)
                    parser_eat(parser, 15)
                    Note: "is less than or equal to" vs "is not less than or equal to"
                    If is_negated is equal to 1:
                        Set comparison_op to 25  Note: TOKEN_GREATER (inverted)
                    Otherwise:
                        Set comparison_op to 27  Note: TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL
                    End If
                End If
                If token_type4 is not equal to 31:  Note: Not TOKEN_OR
                    Note: "is less than" vs "is not less than"
                    If is_negated is equal to 1:
                        Set comparison_op to 26  Note: TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL (inverted)
                    Otherwise:
                        Set comparison_op to 24  Note: TOKEN_LESS
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If token_type3 is not equal to 28:  Note: Not TOKEN_THAN
                Let error_msg be "[PARSER ERROR] Expected 'than' after 'less' at line "
                print_string(error_msg)
                Let line be memory_get_int32(current_token3, 16)
                print_integer(line)
                print_newline()
                exit_with_code(1)
            End If
        End If

        Note: Handle GREATER THAN (and GREATER EQUAL)
        If token_type2 is equal to 25:
            parser_eat(parser, 25)
            Set current_token3 to memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Set token_type3 to memory_get_integer(current_token3, 0)
            If token_type3 is equal to 28:  Note: TOKEN_THAN
                parser_eat(parser, 28)
                Set current_token4 to memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                Set token_type4 to memory_get_integer(current_token4, 0)
                If token_type4 is equal to 31:  Note: TOKEN_OR (for "or equal to")
                    parser_eat(parser, 31)
                    parser_eat(parser, 22)
                    parser_eat(parser, 15)
                    Note: "is greater than or equal to" vs "is not greater than or equal to"
                    If is_negated is equal to 1:
                        Set comparison_op to 24  Note: TOKEN_LESS (inverted)
                    Otherwise:
                        Set comparison_op to 26  Note: TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL
                    End If
                End If
                If token_type4 is not equal to 31:  Note: Not TOKEN_OR
                    Note: "is greater than" vs "is not greater than"
                    If is_negated is equal to 1:
                        Set comparison_op to 27  Note: TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL (inverted)
                    Otherwise:
                        Set comparison_op to 25  Note: TOKEN_GREATER
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If token_type3 is not equal to 28:  Note: Not TOKEN_THAN
                Set error_msg to "[PARSER ERROR] Expected 'than' after 'greater' at line "
                print_string(error_msg)
                Set line to memory_get_int32(current_token3, 16)
                print_integer(line)
                print_newline()
                exit_with_code(1)
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check if we got a valid comparison operator
        Note: If not, treat "is <value>" as shorthand for "is equal to <value>"
        Note: and "is not <value>" as shorthand for "is not equal to <value>"
        If comparison_op is equal to 0:
            Note: The next token is the RHS value - this is the shorthand form
            If is_negated is equal to 1:
                Set comparison_op to 23  Note: TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL
            Otherwise:
                Set comparison_op to 22  Note: TOKEN_EQUAL
            End If
        End If

        Note: Check for "null" / "Null" keyword - treat as 0
        Let null_check be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
        Let null_check_type be memory_get_int32(null_check, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
        Let null_check_val be memory_get_pointer(null_check, TOKEN_VALUE_OFFSET)
        Let is_null_kw be 0
        If null_check_val is not equal to 0:
            If string_equals(null_check_val, "null") is equal to 1:
                Set is_null_kw to 1
            End If
            If string_equals(null_check_val, "Null") is equal to 1:
                Set is_null_kw to 1
            End If
        End If
        If is_null_kw is equal to 1:
            parser_eat(parser, null_check_type)
            Let null_expr be expression_create_integer(0)
            Return expression_create_comparison(left, comparison_op, null_expr)
        End If

        Let right be parser_parse_additive(parser)
        Return expression_create_comparison(left, comparison_op, right)
    End If

    Note: Handle "equals" shorthand: X equals Y → X is equal to Y
    Note: Handle "does not equal" / "does equal" comparison forms
    If token_type is equal to 53:
        Let eq_val be memory_get_pointer(current_token, 8)
        If eq_val is not equal to 0:
            If string_equals(eq_val, "equals") is equal to 1:
                parser_eat(parser, 53)
                Let equals_right be parser_parse_additive(parser)
                Return expression_create_comparison(left, 22, equals_right)
            End If
            If string_equals(eq_val, "does") is equal to 1:
                parser_eat(parser, 53)
                Note: Check for "not" or "equal"
                Let does_next_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
                Let does_next_type be memory_get_int32(does_next_tok, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
                Let does_next_val be memory_get_pointer(does_next_tok, TOKEN_VALUE_OFFSET)
                If does_next_type is equal to 29:
                    Note: TOKEN_NOT - "does not equal"
                    parser_eat(parser, 29)
                    Note: Eat "equal"
                    Let dne_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
                    Let dne_type be memory_get_int32(dne_tok, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
                    parser_eat(parser, dne_type)
                    Let dne_right be parser_parse_additive(parser)
                    Return expression_create_comparison(left, 23, dne_right)
                End If
                If does_next_val is not equal to 0:
                    If string_equals(does_next_val, "equal") is equal to 1:
                        Note: "does equal"
                        parser_eat(parser, does_next_type)
                        Let de_right be parser_parse_additive(parser)
                        Return expression_create_comparison(left, 22, de_right)
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Handle "contains" operator: collection contains value, with optional
    Note: `key` or `index` qualifier:
    Note:   X contains Y          → list_contains(X, Y)
    Note:   X contains key K      → dict_has_key(X, K)
    Note:   X contains index I    → list_contains(X, I)  -- alias of bare form
    If token_type is equal to 179:
        parser_eat(parser, 179)
        Let contains_func_name be string_duplicate_parser("list_contains")
        Let contains_qual_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, PARSER_CURRENT_TOKEN_OFFSET)
        Let contains_qual_type be memory_get_int32(contains_qual_tok, TOKEN_TYPE_OFFSET)
        If contains_qual_type is equal to 150:
            parser_eat(parser, 150)
            Set contains_func_name to string_duplicate_parser("dict_has_key")
        End If
        If contains_qual_type is equal to 149:
            parser_eat(parser, 149)
        End If
        Let contains_right be parser_parse_additive(parser)
        Let contains_args be memory_allocate(16)
        memory_set_pointer(contains_args, 0, left)
        memory_set_pointer(contains_args, 8, contains_right)
        Return expression_create_function_call(contains_func_name, contains_args, 2)
    End If

    Return left
End Process

Note: Parser parse let statement - handles "Let var be expression"
Process called "parser_parse_let_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Grammar (v0.0.8.5 trailing-type-annotation form):
        Let <identifier> be <expression> [of type <type-expression>]
    The pre-value form "Let X as Type be Value" was removed because the AS token
    is ambiguous with multi-word natural-language identifiers containing "as"
    (e.g. "Let my grades as a highschooler be 12"). The new sentinel for an
    explicit type annotation is the two-token sequence "of type" appearing AFTER
    the bound expression. The constructor expression "a value of type T with ..."
    consumes its own "of type" internally inside parser_parse_a_value_of_type, so
    it cannot collide with this trailing form — by the time control returns here
    from parser_parse_expression, the bound expression has fully terminated and
    any remaining "of type" is unambiguously the Let annotation.
    :End Note
    If parser is equal to 0:
        print_string("[PARSER ERROR] NULL parser in parser_parse_let_statement")
        print_newline()
        exit(1)
    End If
    parser_eat(parser, 12)  Note: TOKEN_LET

    Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let token_type be memory_get_integer(current_token, 0)
    Let can_be_id be token_can_be_identifier(token_type)
    If can_be_id is not equal to 1:
        Let error_msg be "[PARSER ERROR] Expected identifier after Let at line "
        print_string(error_msg)
        Let line be memory_get_int32(current_token, 16)
        print_integer(line)
        print_newline()
        exit_with_code(1)
    End If

    Note:
    Multi-word identifier collection (task #95 Stage 2). The caller has
    already verified above that the currently cached token is identifier-
    eligible (token_can_be_identifier returned 1), which is the precondition
    that parser_collect_multiword_identifier assumes. The collector reads
    the first word's value, eats the first token, then loop-consumes any
    following tokens that satisfy token_can_continue_identifier — joining
    them with single underscores per the D8 canonicalization decision. For
    a single-word source (e.g. "my_count"), the loop exits immediately and
    the returned name is byte-identical to what the previous single-token
    path produced. The compiler source itself uses no multi-word Let
    binding names, so emitted output remains byte-identical to Stage 1.
    :End Note
    Let var_name be parser_collect_multiword_identifier(parser)

    Note:
    TOKEN_AS (34) after the Let identifier is NOT a parser error. The pre-value
    "Let X as Type be V" form was removed at v0.0.8.5 by lifting the type
    annotation to the trailing "of type T" position, which frees the AS token
    to serve as a normal continuation token inside multi-word natural-language
    identifiers (e.g. "Let my grades as a highschooler be 12"). Until the
    multi-word identifier parser lands (task #95), a source that uses the old
    typed-let form will reach the parser_eat(parser, 13) below and fail with a
    plain "Expected TOKEN_BE" diagnostic from the eater — same behaviour as any
    other malformed statement. No bespoke rejection here would survive the
    multi-word migration, so emitting one would create a false-positive trap
    for valid future syntax. The trailing "of type T" annotation is recognised
    below after parser_parse_expression returns.
    :End Note

    parser_eat(parser, 13)  Note: TOKEN_BE

    If parser is equal to 0:
        print_string("[PARSER ERROR] parser became NULL before expression parsing in Let")
        print_newline()
        exit(1)
    End If

    Let expr be parser_parse_expression(parser)

    Note:
    Optional trailing type annotation: "of type <TypeName>[.QualifiedName][<GenericArgs>]".
    Recognise only the exact two-token sequence "of" followed by "type". The
    second token may be TOKEN_TYPE (50, the keyword) or any token whose word
    value is "type" — the constructor parser accepts both so the trailing form
    must too. We use the lexer save/restore peek pattern (mirroring
    parser_peek_struct_field_after_comma) to confirm the second token without
    committing to a parse if it turns out to be something else. This matters
    because plain TOKEN_OF (125) appears in many other postfix-style positions
    (length of X, substring of X, position of X in Y) — consuming it eagerly
    here would corrupt those constructs when the bound expression happens to
    end on something the host expression parser could not consume.
    :End Note
    Let let_type_name be 0
    Let trail_check be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let trail_check_type be memory_get_integer(trail_check, 0)
    If trail_check_type is equal to 125:
        Let trail_lexer be memory_get_pointer(parser, 0)
        Let trail_saved_pos be memory_get_int32(trail_lexer, 8)
        Let trail_saved_line be memory_get_int32(trail_lexer, 12)
        Let trail_saved_col be memory_get_int32(trail_lexer, 16)
        Let trail_saved_char be memory_get_byte(trail_lexer, 20)
        Let trail_is_of_type be 0
        Let trail_next_tok be lexer_next_token(trail_lexer)
        If trail_next_tok is not equal to 0:
            Let trail_next_type be memory_get_integer(trail_next_tok, 0)
            If trail_next_type is equal to 50:
                Set trail_is_of_type to 1
            End If
            Let trail_next_val be memory_get_pointer(trail_next_tok, 8)
            If trail_is_of_type is equal to 0:
                If trail_next_val is not equal to 0:
                    Let trail_word_eq be string_equals(trail_next_val, "type")
                    If trail_word_eq is equal to 1:
                        Set trail_is_of_type to 1
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            token_destroy(trail_next_tok)
        End If
        memory_set_int32(trail_lexer, 8, trail_saved_pos)
        memory_set_int32(trail_lexer, 12, trail_saved_line)
        memory_set_int32(trail_lexer, 16, trail_saved_col)
        memory_set_byte(trail_lexer, 20, trail_saved_char)

        If trail_is_of_type is equal to 1:
            parser_eat(parser, 125)  Note: Eat 'of'

            Let trail_type_kw be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let trail_type_kw_type be memory_get_integer(trail_type_kw, 0)
            If trail_type_kw_type is equal to 50:
                parser_eat(parser, 50)
            Otherwise:
                parser_eat(parser, trail_type_kw_type)
            End If

            Let trail_name_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let trail_name_type be memory_get_integer(trail_name_token, 0)
            Let trail_name_val be memory_get_pointer(trail_name_token, 8)
            If trail_name_val is not equal to 0:
                Set let_type_name to string_duplicate_parser(trail_name_val)
            End If
            Let trail_name_can_id be token_can_be_identifier(trail_name_type)
            If trail_name_can_id is equal to 1:
                parser_eat(parser, trail_name_type)
            Otherwise:
                parser_eat(parser, 53)
            End If

            Note:
            Optional ".QualifiedTypeName" suffix. Use the part after the dot
            as the resolved type name (the module prefix is source-level only;
            codegen looks types up by their bare name in the merged program
            scope).
            :End Note
            Let trail_dot_check be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let trail_dot_type be memory_get_integer(trail_dot_check, 0)
            If trail_dot_type is equal to 51:
                parser_eat(parser, 51)
                Let trail_qual_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                Let trail_qual_type be memory_get_integer(trail_qual_token, 0)
                Let trail_qual_val be memory_get_pointer(trail_qual_token, 8)
                If trail_qual_val is not equal to 0:
                    Set let_type_name to string_duplicate_parser(trail_qual_val)
                End If
                Let trail_qual_can_id be token_can_be_identifier(trail_qual_type)
                If trail_qual_can_id is equal to 1:
                    parser_eat(parser, trail_qual_type)
                Otherwise:
                    parser_eat(parser, 53)
                End If
            End If

            Note:
            Skip generic params after the type name (e.g. "of type List[Integer]").
            TOKEN_LBRACKET = 127, TOKEN_RBRACKET = 128. Eat all tokens until
            the matching close bracket (handle nested brackets too).
            :End Note
            Let trail_gen_check be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
            Let trail_gen_type be memory_get_integer(trail_gen_check, 0)
            If trail_gen_type is equal to 127:
                parser_eat(parser, 127)
                Let trail_bracket_depth be 1
                While trail_bracket_depth is greater than 0:
                    Let trail_gen_inner_tok be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
                    Let trail_gen_inner_type be memory_get_integer(trail_gen_inner_tok, 0)
                    If trail_gen_inner_type is equal to 127:
                        Set trail_bracket_depth to trail_bracket_depth plus 1
                        parser_eat(parser, 127)
                    Otherwise If trail_gen_inner_type is equal to 128:
                        Set trail_bracket_depth to trail_bracket_depth minus 1
                        parser_eat(parser, 128)
                    Otherwise If trail_gen_inner_type is equal to 0:
                        Note: TOKEN_EOF guard against runaway loops
                        Set trail_bracket_depth to 0
                    Otherwise:
                        parser_eat(parser, trail_gen_inner_type)
                    End If
                End While
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let let_stmt be statement_create_let(var_name, expr)
    If let_type_name is not equal to 0:
        statement_set_let_type(let_stmt, let_type_name)
    End If
    Return let_stmt
End Process

Note: Parser parse set statement - handles "Set target to expression"
Process called "parser_parse_implicit_compound_assign" takes parser as Integer, operation as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse implicit compound assignment: Increase/Decrease/Multiply/Divide X by Y
    Note: operation: 0=add, 1=sub, 2=mul, 3=div

    Note: Eat the operation token (INCREASE/DECREASE/MULTIPLY/DIVIDE)
    Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let token_type be memory_get_int32(current_token, 0)
    parser_eat(parser, token_type)

    Note: Parse target variable/expression
    Let target be parser_parse_expression(parser)

    Note: Eat BY token (38)
    parser_eat(parser, 38)

    Note: Parse value expression
    Let expr be parser_parse_expression(parser)

    Note: Create compound assignment statement
    Let stmt be statement_create_compound_assign(target, operation, expr)
    Return stmt
End Process

Process called "parser_parse_set_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    parser_eat(parser, 14)

    Note: Parse the target expression (could be variable or nested field access)
    Let target be parser_parse_expression(parser)

    Note: Check for compound assignment: gets [increased|decreased|multiplied|divided] by
    Let current_token be memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
    Let token_type be memory_get_int32(current_token, 0)

    Note: TOKEN_GETS is 136
    If token_type is equal to 136:
        Note: This is a compound assignment: Set X gets [op] by Y
        parser_eat(parser, 136)

        Note: Get operation token
        Set current_token to memory_get_pointer(parser, 8)
        Set token_type to memory_get_int32(current_token, 0)

        Let operation be 0
        Note: TOKEN_INCREASED is 137, TOKEN_DECREASED is 138
        Note: TOKEN_MULTIPLIED is 35, TOKEN_DIVIDED is 36
        Note: TOKEN_MULTIPLY is 141, TOKEN_DIVIDE is 142
        If token_type is equal to 137:
            Set operation to 0
            parser_eat(parser, 137)
        End If
        If token_type is equal to 138:
            Set operation to 1
            parser_eat(parser, 138)
        End If
        If token_type is equal to 35:
            Set operation to 2
            parser_eat(parser, 35)
        End If
        If token_type is equal to 141:
            Set operation to 2
            parser_eat(parser, 141)
        End If
        If token_type is equal to 36:
            Set operation to 3
            parser_eat(parser, 36)
        End If
        If token_type is equal to 142:
            Set operation to 3
            parser_eat(parser, 142)
        End If
        If operation is equal to 0:
            If token_type is not equal to 137:
                print_string("Parser error: Expected operation after gets (got token ")
                print_integer(token_type)
                print_string(")")
                print_newline()
                exit_with_code(1)
            End If
        End If

        parser_eat(parser, 38)

        Let expr be parser_parse_expression(parser)

        Let stmt be statement_create_compound_assign(target, operation, expr)
        Return stmt
    End If

    Note: Normal set statement: Set X to Y
    parser_eat(parser, 15)

    Set expr to parser_parse_expression(parser)

    Set stmt to statement_create_set(target, expr)
    Return stmt
End Process

